<Input>
<Text-field style="Text" size="16" layout="Normal"><Font size="16">There are a few points to note about the irrotational vortex.  First, it is singular at the origin.  Second, the vorticity away from the origin is zero (hence the name).  The flip side of this is that ALL the vorticity is concentrated at the origin (as a delta function).  Third, the rate of strain tensor shows that all the entries are non-zero, though they decay with distance from the origin. Fourth even though the individual entries of the rate of strain are non-zero the net viscous force (proportional to e_ij,j or div <Font bold="true">e</Font>) is zero.  This is a very powerful fact.  Physically it tells you that it is possible to have deformation without a net viscous force.</Font></Text-field>
</Input>
</Group>
